Day 07 - var, let, and const
Topics Learned
var
let
const
Variable Reassignment
Modern JavaScript Variable Rules
What is ES6?

ES6 (ECMAScript 2015) is a major JavaScript update that introduced many modern features used in React and modern web development.

var

Old way of creating variables.

var name = "Atharv";

console.log(name);

Value can be changed:

var age = 18;

age = 19;

console.log(age);

Output:

19
let

Modern way of creating variables.

let city = "Pune";

city = "Mumbai";

console.log(city);

Output:

Mumbai
Key Point
Value can be changed.
Preferred over var.
const

Used for values that should not change.

const country = "India";

console.log(country);

Output:

India

Trying to change a const variable:

const country = "India";

country = "USA";

Output:

Error: Assignment to constant variable
Comparison
Keyword	Can Change Value?
var	Yes
let	Yes
const	No
Mini Task
const name = "Atharv";

let score = 0;

score = 100;

console.log(name);
console.log(score);

Output:

Atharv
100
Best Practice
const name = "Atharv";
let score = 0;

Use:

const by default
let when the value needs to change
Avoid var in modern JavaScript
Key Takeaways
var is the older way to declare variables.
let allows reassignment.
const prevents reassignment.
Modern JavaScript mainly uses let and const.
Prefer const whenever possible.
